{{Speciesbox | image = Moringa stenopetala.jpg | genus = Moringa | species = stenopetala | authority = ([[Edmund Gilbert Baker|Baker f.]]) [[Georg Cufodontis|Cufod.]]<ref name="grin1">&nbsp;Under its current treatment of ''Moringa stenopetala'' (from its basionym, ''Donaldsonia stenopetala''), this species was published in ''Senckenbergiana Biologica'' 38: 407. 1957. {{GRIN | accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref> | synonyms = *''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' <small>Baker f.</small> ([[basionym]]) * ''Moringa streptocarpa'' <small>[[Emilio Chiovenda|Chiov.]]</small> | synonyms_ref = <ref name=grin1/><ref name="grin2">&nbsp;The basionym of ''Moringa stenopetala'', ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'', was first described and published in ''Journal of Botany, British and Foreign'' 1896: 53. 1896. {{GRIN | ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' | 424400 | accessdate = January 1, 2012}}</ref> }}
'''''Moringa stenopetala''''', commonly called the '''cabbage-tree'''<ref name=grin1/> (along with a number of other species), is a tree in the flowering plant genus ''[[Moringa]]'', native to [[Kenya]] and [[Ethiopia]].<ref name="AAA2015">{{cite journal | vauthors = Leone A, Spada A, Battezzati A, Schiraldi A, Aristil J, Bertoli S | title = Cultivation, Genetic, Ethnopharmacology, Phytochemistry and Pharmacology of ''Moringa oleifera'' Leaves: An Overview | journal = International Journal of Molecular Sciences | volume = 16 | pages = 12791–12835 | year = 2015 | doi = 10.3390/ijms160612791 | pmid=26057747 | pmc=4490473}}</ref> It is now extirpated in the wild in Ethiopia, though still grown there as a crop on the terraces built to conserve water high up the mountains.<ref name=grin1/> It is a multipurpose tree producing edible leaves, seeds used for the purification of water, and traditional medicinal products.
==History== The cabbage-tree was planted by agriculturalists on the complex system of terraces built high up in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], where they became domesticated and were bred to improve productivity, the taste of their leaves, and the size of their seeds. Since then, the improved trees have been introduced into other areas such as the [[Great Rift Valley, Kenya|Rift Valley]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Samia Al Azharia Jahn |year=1991 |title=The Traditional Domestication of a Multipurpose Tree ''Moringa stenopetala'' (Bak.f.) Cuf. in the Ethiopian Rift Valley |journal=Ambio |volume=20 |issue=6 |pages=244–247 |jstor=4313833 }}</ref>
==Description== The cabbage-tree is a small tree up to {{convert|12|m|0|abbr=on}}, with a many-branched crown and sometimes with multiple trunks. The leaves are bipinnate or tripinnate, with about five pairs of pinnae and three to nine elliptic or ovate leaflets on each pinna. The fragrant flowers have creamy-pink sepals, white or yellow petals, and white stamens. The fruits are long reddish pods with a greyish bloom.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.seedvendor.com/50--seeds-moringa-stenopetala--african-moringa-cabbage--tr50.html |title=''Moringa stenopetala'': African Moringa |publisher=Seed People |accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref>
==Uses== ''Moringa stenopetala'' is mostly known for its importance as a nutritious [[vegetable]] food crop in the [[terrace (agriculture)|terraced]] fields of [[Konso]], [[Ethiopia]]. In this way, it is similar to its Indian relative, ''[[Moringa oleifera]]''.<ref>[http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sitefactsheet.php?id=6297 "Birdlife Data Zone: Konso - Segen"], Birdlife International website . Retrieved 15 January 2011.</ref><ref name="TreesforLife">{{cite web |url=http://www.treesforlife.org/documents/moringa/presentation/Moringa%20Presentation%20%28General%29%20screen.pdf |title=The Moringa Tree ''Moringa oleifera'' |publisher=Trees for Life International |accessdate=2011-01-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621093813/http://www.treesforlife.org/documents/moringa/presentation/Moringa%20Presentation%20%28General%29%20screen.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-21 |df= }}</ref> It is also used for shading of ''[[Capsicum]]'' and ''[[Sorghum]]'' crops, as a [[companion planting|companion plant]];<ref name=grin1/> and additionally in [[folk medicine]].<ref name=grin1/>
Another use is the clarification and purification of water to make it potable. A powder made by grinding the seeds is found to be more effective at coagulating substances in suspension than the seeds of the closely related [[Moringa oleifera|horseradish tree]] (''M. oleifera''), which is used for this purpose in India.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3362/0262-8104.1985.019 |title=Water purification with ''Moringa'' seeds |year=1985 |last1=Desa |first1=Dian |journal=Waterlines |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=22–3}}</ref>
